customers_scale %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(annual_income_k, spending_score_1_100),
               names_to = "type", 
               values_to = "value") %>% #convert data to long format
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(mean = round(mean(value)), 
            sd = sd(value))
fviz_nbclust(customers_scale,
             kmeans,
             method = "wss",
             nstart = 25)

fviz_nbclust(customers_scale,
             kmeans,
             method = "silhouette",
             nstart = 25)

fviz_nbclust(customers_scale,
             kmeans,
             method = "gap_stat",
             nstart = 25,
             k.max = 10)

clusterings <- k_clusters %>%
  unnest(glanced)
clusterings %>%
  unnest(cols = c(augmented)) %>%
  filter(k == 5) %>%
  ggplot(aes(annual_income_k, spending_score_1_100)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = .cluster)) +
  scale_colour_discrete(labels = c("L income/H spender",
                                 "L income/L spender",
                                 "H income/L spender",
                                 "H income/H spender",
                                 "M income/M spender"),
                        name = "Cluster")

The clustering is a good fit, all clusters seem to be nicely grouped. The high income and low spending group would be a good group to target, in general they’ll have more disposable income and with the correct marketing, it will potentially increase their spending score dramatically
